I totally understand those who are saying they dislike Day 30 because Adriene is not speaking and guiding us. It's hard for me as well. But like, that's the whole point, right? It's supposed to be a little bit of a challenge. Step out of your comfort zone for a bit. The reason you've been following along these past 29 days with Adriene is so that you will have the tools and techniques you need to "build your own" yoga session. When you just let go of that negative voice inside you that says "I can't do this without Adriene guiding me," or "I hate this," you will find that you CAN do it! It doesn't matter if it's the most "professional" yoga session - it's what feels good for YOU. That's the idea, right? Find what feels good! Even if it's just you sitting still and quiet for 25 minutes, for some of us, that's enough of a practice because we so rarely get to do that. The poses don't matter as much as your attitude on (and off) the mat. Even if you feel silly, who cares? You know the poses by now. YOU CAN DO IT! Namaste to all of you! :)

I just went into my head and followed my body and my heart and did "what felt good".  I was really involved in myself and enjoying it when I noticed the music change and thought "hmm...this is usually the final resting pose music and looked at the TV - I was surprised to see the session was wrapping up.  I am SO glad I found my way back to daily practice - I feel mentally and physically better.  Love Adriene's philosophy and her "not so serious" moments too.

This was my second 30 days of yoga and this day is always so scary in the beginging. 

You feel tears start to well up when you begin in seated meditations but then as the poses start something the tears turn to laughs because your body magically knows what to do. 

You try the poses constatnly glancing to see if you are doing them right and then look away to try it by yourself and successfully begin to move into the next one as Adriene does and you feel TRUE (haha get it?) success!

Then comes the part where she slyly look at the camera and begins to do a pose that she murdered you in days ago but you laugh because it is like you shared a private joke. 

Next comes the part where you stay in child's pose too long and when you look up again she is in forward fold. It humbles you because you will forever have things to learn. 

Finally, it comes back and the flow begins, only to end abpruptly as the hands are placed on the head and you "hear" her say Namaste as you say it aloud. 

Thank you so much for these practices Adriene. We love you so much and you have taught us to always be true. 

Namaste.

I did not think that this month was going to give me all that it has. My only goal for these 30 days was to strengthen my mind and I got so much more in addition. I have tried so many other ways to start caring for my body the way that it deserves and nothing has ever worked. I would start, but not be able to stick with it long enough because it just never felt right. I stopped looking at the scale and picking myself apart in a mirror. Instead of those things, I journaled after every practice. I can look back on those entries and see so much progress in the way that I practice, the thoughts that I had, and my willpower to care for myself. While I wasn't looking, I lost a noticeable amount of weight. This is without stepping on a scale or even staring intently at a mirror. I notice in the way that my clothes fit just a little bit better. This wasn't even about losing weight when I started, but taking care of my mind led to taking care of my body. And now both are thanking me. This has debunked so many myths of what I thought yoga was and who it was for. Thank you, Adriene, for this journey and for making me feel like I belonged on my own mat.

I finished the challenge today, took me 32 or 33 days. It's incredible the power of this journey!
It made me accept things as they are and not worry too much, to work with the problems that we got now, and not worry too much about the next minute or hour. 
I had to record some videos for my instagram influencer account and I had to sing, and yoga  has helped me with singing  for years. And my journey with singing has been hard. 
I've been through fights with people that hurted me and I thought were not supposed to, I got frustrated, I would beat myself up everyday (if I sand bad, I was a piece of shit, if I sang good, then it was what it was supposed to be, no congratulations for me, and I better get it right next time too), I looked for approval from others (cause I couldn't get it from myself) and even when they complimented me I wouldn't believe them. I would thing they were making fun of me or didn't know what they were saying... Yes, I was putting singing before myself. Singing before being, enjoying.
Around a year ago I started loosing creativity (which was always something natural in me) and I became really tired and didn't sing that much. I still tried because I was supposed to, but I couldn't because I was too tired of this.

At first I didn't like the idea of you not guiding us through this one, but then I realized it was about not expecting others to tell you what to do. So I started following you, but also kinda doing my thing. And it felt really good.

Today yoga wasn't about singing. This whole 30 days you made me do ssomething that wasn't for singing. I'm tearing up right now.
Today yoga was for and about myself. And I really needed that. 

So thank you so much for being yourself, you helped me be myself too, in a time where I really needed it. And I started to taste what loving myself felt like, when I really needed it. My journey to this point started a really long time ago, but this challenge really helped me establish the idea that it is okay. What's good, what's bad, what's meh or blah, all of those are okay. And I also learned other beautiful things with you.

I rewinded the video at the end to bow and I bowed to you. I started sheading tears at the end. Because I realized how much I have changed and how far I've come. I wouldn't have finished this in the past. And last year maybe I would've forced it.
But this time it felt really good. So thank you.
I bowed to you because I felt really grateful that you made this practice for us, and you were so soothing and positive and understanding the whole time.

my lovely Adriene, I am 24 and since I was 16 I had a love for yoga. back then I didn't know what I was doing and once I tried to copy a power yoga class I found online, failed miserably and quited. At 19 I joined a gym, I hated it at the most part but I loved going to yoga classes. I was terrible at it, 60year olds were flowing like the wind beside me and I was sweating like a pig just doing downward dog. Needless to say the instructor corrected every single pose I did, and mostly, downward dog. I loved yoga but it made me feel really insecure especially when the whole class had to stop until I got it right.so I stopped going. last year I went back. the instructor remembered me and considered me advanced so she pushed me to do a handstand(the whole class stopped again to watch me, and to my surprise I succeeded!), but as I was standing upside down a wave of panic washed over me and I fell and at that moment I realized I was doing it all wrong; yoga isn't supposed to give you panic attacks. so I stopped going, again, but the itch for yoga didn't go away. and then I found you, and this challenge. to be honest I didn't complete the challenge in a month (try two) because I missed days in between due to my terrible habit of quitting, but what I wanted to say is that for the first time, because of you, I took yoga seriously, learned to flow without worrying and did a yoga flow(this one) without someone constantly correcting me and telling me what to do(which is something I never dared  dream to try), and for just this once I didn't care that my downward dog isn't good; I enjoyed the process. and I have to thank solely you for that. with this long ass comment I commit to the universe to continue yoga no matter how, where or with whom. (P.S. I completed the challenge without owning a yoga mat, I used towels, beddings and blankets, but a yoga mat goes into my list). lots of love, namaste

This is my 3rd 30 day challenge this year. I just have to speak up, this is the best thing I've ever done for myself. At the end of 2017 I felt I wanted to start my days mindfully and stop rushing away to work or training, not collecting myself and feeling what's up today. I had my "own" little flow through January but I felt lost and didn't know what to do. I had heard about Adriene so I found the original 30 day practice from jan 2015. I performed one session in the morning and one before bedtime, same session twice. I also felt I had trouble overeating before bedtime so I needed something to collect my thoughts at that time of day as well. It was A really good start with lots of yoga movements as you might want to expect of a yoga practice (which was good!!) I got really hooked and after 30 days I started another 30 day challenge doing 2 days in one day, one in the morning, the next in the evening and third next day and so on. Went to Thailand for 2,5 weeks and tried to keep going but it wasn't that easy as I thought. So getting back home I had really got off track which I felt. I was back rushing in the morning and eating at night. I decided to go for it again and found this 30day challenge. All I can say is during this time, and especially this 30 days I've increased my self love by 300 %. I have FELT the words that Adriene has spoken to me (us) and I've never been more happy with my self. THIS we call yoga or meditation och mindfullness - this makes me a better person towards me. And that makes me a better person towards everyone else. There are not enough words to describe how thankful I am to have this experience with myself, Al thanks to you Adriene. Looking forward to my upcoming 30 days with me (and you ;)) anyone looking for anything - this is the answer. Lots of love /S

Adriene I super love you and am SO grateful for this channel. I have watched you for years and recommended you to dozens of others. 
But I have to say how much I hate these silent videos!!! Why on earth do you do these? I only wish I weren‚Äôt so OCD as to have to finish all 30 days of 30 day yoga. 
Your silence gives us four options:1) Ignore the video and do our own thing. I do enjoy doing this sometimes, but why bother turning on YouTube for that?2) Watch the video but do nothing. (Or I guess theoretically there is a fifth option to watch the video to memorize it and do later.) Both options seem like a poor use of time. 3) Try to generally follow what you are doing but be in the moment. I am guessing this is what you think we are doing, but it makes the practice just a long series of terrible transitions and imbalance (catching the full warrior for my right leg but only a few seconds for my left, for example.) This is what I have done in the past and it is extremely unsatisfying. 4) Today I just kept my eyes on you the whole time while following what you did for the sake of balance and good transitions. This of course did not allow me to do any one posture correctly as my neck was always jacked to see what you were doing. 
If there is a good sixth option then please tell me, because all of the above options accomplish the exact opposite of what you have been trying to teach this whole time. 
So as to not waste (or leave as counterproductive) these last videos, you could publish alternate endings with you narrating what you are doing. That way I could complete each 30 day set feeling happy and proud of myself rather than imbalanced, with a jacked neck, and frustrated.
I need to follow your voice, this practice makes me anxious.

This is my third 30-day challenge in the last few months. I started my second challenge (Revolution) about a week after because I wanted something to help me keep a somewhat consistent practice. By Day 30, I felt a little more brave and found my own flow for about 15 minutes, yet I'm not sure if I was listening to my body or just trying to remember flow sequences that I had done in the past. Today, I closed my eyes and practiced for the entire 30 minutes, and was surprised when the music stopped and the video ended. Something in my practice shifted during TRUE, and I can't thank you enough, Adriene, for being a patient, understanding, and consistent teacher throughout this process. So happy to hear there is more to continue my journey. My professional career has left me disappointed and feeling stuck. True has allowed me the freedom and movement to find what serves me and to rid me of that which does not. While I enjoyed the strenuous physical challenge and the significant improvements in my comfort, flexibility and muscle tone the philosophy behind True really spoke to me and my current daily challenges. I end every practice with reminding myself to see the truth, speak the truth and feel truth. I found the daily pins to be especially enlightening.  

I got emotional during this last practice, in the video you smiled in a challenging plank pose and it reminded me to smile and at that moment I felt I was really practicing yoga with a best friend. I started laughing as I felt empowered and happy that I am and have actively pursued taking care of me, loving me for me faults and all. I started to get emotional at the reflection of what it means to commit to myself, something I have not always done. 
 
 The insight gained and difference in perspective from TRUE is what I found to be most gratifying about this challenge. And I am so proud of myself that I have completed 30 full days of daily yoga practice. Something I have been wanting to do since I began practicing yoga some five years ago. There were so many restrictions I was putting on my practice for it "to count." If it wasn't an hour long practice, in a peaceful distract free environment I felt I wasn't doing it right, or wasn't correctly practicing yoga and would constrict my practice only to when these conditions were met. I used to feel thrown off when I would get dog paws on my mat, reflecting back I was way to rigid with my practice. I had previously only experienced yoga through 60-90 minute paid classes at yoga studios. Where they have isolated peaceful practice areas, they spritz lavender over your face during corpse pose. This was the yoga experience I came to understand as how true yogi's practice true authentic yoga, or so I thought...

Watching YWA I saw a different way to practice yoga. I love that my dog comes on the mat now & I don't mind the foot prints anymore.  I no longer wait for peace to come before I seek yoga, I find peace away from distractions and noise through yoga and quieting the mind. In one video, you challenged us to pay attention to what we hear outside. You mentioned that you heard a siren outside your window. I found this ironic as this is the most cringe worthy opposite of peaceful sound one can think of.  You changed how I viewed what yoga is and means, yoga has as much power as you allow it to have.  For this change in mindset I am so grateful to what you have shared with all of us. There are perspectives, insights and new philosophies I have gained from the last 30 days that could have taken me a lifetime to notice had I not found YWA. You are truly an inspiration to me and I so appreciate you producing these videos for free as I am rich in spirit but not monetarily. I read through the comments after classes and feel I have found a community of my own. I can not thank you enough but I can say I feel love for you and I know what I'll do when judgement comes for me bum bum bom bom bom...:)
Thank you so much. That was the most amazing, enlightening and loving yoga I have ever done. I love you, Adriene. Bless you.

I'm a few days late to Day 30 and when I got here I was so scared and nervous at first, thinking "What does she mean take the mic off???" I went ahead in the video and my fear was confirmed: No Adriene's voice to guide me through this. I thought about skipping this and doing a different video for today, but then I read through the comments and began to understand. This practice is not about following along with Adriene--you're not supposed to take peeks at what she's doing and follow along. You're supposed to listen to your body, create your own "yoga flow" and "find what feels good."  I decided to be brave and fearless and aware and kind and... ME! I accepted the challenge and I'm so happy I did. I never would have thought I could do yoga without a guide. But I listened to what my body needed. I did all the warriors, I did back rolls, I did planks with hip dips!!! And I feel awesome! I feel empowered! My motive on day one was to get more in touch with myself. I am already pretty fit, but I don't know when to push myself and when to take breaks (both in life and in fitness). This practice forced me to listen to myself. I have already begun to achieve my goal.  I cannot thank you enough Adriene. There is a reason you have 3M subscribers--and it's not just cuz free yoga.  THANK YOU so much for all you do for each and every one of us. <3

Thank you Adrienne for the 30 day yoga series. 
This was just what I needed going into this new year (and getting a year older). This is going to be a too long didn't read post but I will go on anyways :).
I did well up until the Day 14th. By well I mean I showed up, stayed the time, did my best to follow the techniques.
However, the scary flu this season did not spare me and I got really ill. I had to discontinue my practice few days then had to double up on some days. I had the flu ...from worst to still bad, for 3 weeks.
I finally managed to complete the 30th day this afternoon (Feb 1st). 
It would have been a shame to give up (as in I had really come this far and sometimes one NEEDs to finish what one has started for their own peace of mind).  So, I DID complete the 30 days challenge.
Here are few more (eye rolls**) things I  would like to share:
1. I did not, ever, get some of the poses right. And some days, I did not get the poses right which I did previously.
2. I never really achieved the balance (trembling legs up until the last day! :P). Will keep trying.
3. Bakashana (crow pose)... NOPE! Hope to get better at it.
4. Breathing... (ah well.. who knew I didn't know how to breathe!) I followed the pattern mostly, but sometimes.. well just went with it.
5. The sessions were consistently funny with silly pop culture references  and just the right amount of yogic vocabulary that I could follow. And I really appreciated Adrienne's pace, chilled tone and validation of how it is ok if some of us were struggling with some steps. I also kinda missed Benji when he/she wasn't there.
6. Finally, what next? Well there are loads of other videos on YwA channel and then.. yeah.. there's that crow pose to conquer.
Oh yes, I feel much better physically and I lost few pounds (although sickness and loss of appetite may also have contributed to the loss). Mentally or moodwise, I always thought it was a cliched thing people say but I do feel happier (if only because I followed through but I know it is more than that).
Massive Thanks!

Oh Adriene. Where do I begin?

I began this journey because I saw your video about it in my suggested feed towards the end of December, and decided I'd start and go along with it. I thought it'd be fun, and may be helpful. Boy was I in for a treat.

This journey has been the sole thing to truly help me overcome hurdles I've been stumbling over. I've struggled with anorexia for several years, and a few weeks back (right before beginning this journey) I was facing impending hospitalization for it.

This has been the first thing to really sink in for me. Learning the mind and body connection I've never had has nothing short of changed my life in one month. Most of the horrible demons have melted off my back. You taught me to trust myself. To love myself. To be myself.¬†

I have a long way to go, but this journey you've cultivated has entirely changed the game for me. You may have even saved my life, because I've never had this much desire to take care of myself and accept myself instead of starving and doing intense cardio. You've taught me how to find what feels good.¬†

I can't thank you enough. I'm so blessed to consider myself in your tribe now. TRUE has been my favorite part of every day, and I intend to continue using your practices every day. TRUE has been a therapeutic, healing process that's helped me progress in mentally fighting my disorder more than therapy has. I'm still not healthy, but TRUE has helped me correlate listening to my mind and body connection in other areas off the matt-- suddenly being able to fight the urges to over exercise, enjoying fruit again knowing that it's nourishing me just like TRUE is nourishing my soul, and showing me that the courage to fight has been inside all along. I don't have to go out like this. I can truly fight it off for good and have this be the year I find peace, maybe even a healthier weight later down the road, and so much more.

I'm not crying, you're crying.

Namaste, ¬†my friend.

I'm saving this to do with a friend to celebrate the last day of the challenge. TRUE was the first yoga challenge I've ever committed to and actually finished, and the first challenge in general over the last few years that I've stuck to. I found that I NEED practicing in the morning. Not even want... need. Even if I don't want to do it, I make myself do it anyway and modify as needed. I also learned to listen to my body and do what works for me.
